"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573744","Department of Health","false","2016-09-12","<p>There were 26 clinical commissioning groups rated as inadequate for 2015-16. The ratings do not go into such a degree of granularity as to reference specific services or treatments (for example IVF provision).</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-12T14:32:52.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573744/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573744/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-02","Fertility: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 July 2016, to Question 42888, how many clinical commissioning groups were rated as inadequate for 2015-16; and how many such inadequate ratings given in relation, at least in part, to poor IVF provision.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573745","Department of Health","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department published an impact assessment on the Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards in 2008; it has made no further estimate. The Law Commission’s review of the safeguards, which has been commissioned by the Department, is expected to be published at the end of the year.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-12T16:50:07.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573745/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573745/answer",,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-02","Mental Capacity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the financial cost to local authorities of Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards for people who are placed in care homes or hospitals for their care or treatment.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573746","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government began work to implement the ‘Dubs amendment’ immediately after the Immigration Bill gained Royal Assent. Over 30 children who meet the criteria in the Immigration Act have been accepted for transfer since it received Royal Assent in May, the majority of these have already arrived in the UK.</p><p>We continue to work with the French, Greek and Italian authorities and others to speed up existing family reunification processes or implement new processes where necessary for unaccompanied children. We have seconded a UK official to Greece, we have a long-standing secondee working in Italy and will shortly be seconding another official to the French Interior Ministry to support these efforts.</p><p>We have established a dedicated team in the Home Office Dublin Unit to lead on family reunion cases for unaccompanied children. Transfer requests under the Dublin Regulation are now generally processed within 10 days and children transferred within weeks. Over 120 children have been accepted for transfer this year from Europe.</p><p>We also continue to consult local authorities about the transfer of unaccompanied refugee children from Europe to the UK, where it is in their best interests.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:43:13.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573746/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573746/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to accelerate the reunification of families for unaccompanied refugee children in Europe.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","44508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573747","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government began work to implement the ‘Dubs amendment’ immediately after the Immigration Bill gained Royal Assent. Over 30 children who meet the criteria in the Immigration Act have been accepted for transfer since it received Royal Assent in May, the majority of these have already arrived in the UK.</p><p>We continue to work with the French, Greek and Italian authorities and others to speed up existing family reunification processes or implement new processes where necessary for unaccompanied children. We have seconded a UK official to Greece, we have a long-standing secondee working in Italy and will shortly be seconding another official to the French Interior Ministry to support these efforts.</p><p>We have established a dedicated team in the Home Office Dublin Unit to lead on family reunion cases for unaccompanied children. Transfer requests under the Dublin Regulation are now generally processed within 10 days and children transferred within weeks. Over 120 children have been accepted for transfer this year from Europe.</p><p>We also continue to consult local authorities about the transfer unaccompanied refugee children from Europe to the UK, where it is in their best interests.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:27:43.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573747/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573747/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to accelerate the process of family reunification for unaccompanied refugee children in Europe.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","44498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573748","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Home Office launched a Tier 4 visa pilot involving the Universities of Oxford, Cambridge and Bath and Imperial College London on 25 July. The pilot has been introduced to test the benefits of a differentiated approach within the education sector on the basis of compliance with immigration sponsorship requirements.</p><p>The pilot is deliberately narrow in scope, with the institutions selected on the basis of their consistently low level of visa refusals. Visa refusal rates are part of the Basic Compliance Assessment, which requires all Tier 4 sponsors to meet three core requirements based on measures of visa refusals, enrolment and completion of studies.</p><p>The limited nature of the pilot is intended to ensure that the outcomes can be adequately monitored, whilst minimising the risk of unintended consequences, before considering rolling-out the scheme more widely.</p><p>The four selected institutions were consulted regarding its implementation. Should the pilot be successful and rolled out more widely, the Home Office will consult key stakeholders about its expansion.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","44187","2016-09-12T15:45:18.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573748/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573748/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of using institutional visa refusal rates as a indicator of institutional compliance with Tier 4 visa regulations.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","44549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573749","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>In the year ending June 2016, 49% (1,308) of those resettled under the Syrian Vulnerable Person’s Resettlement Scheme (VPRS) were under 18 years old. In April 2016 the Home Office announced a new scheme to resettle vulnerable children from the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region. We have worked closely with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to design this scheme.</p><p>Since the beginning of this year, over 120 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in Europe have been accepted for transfer to the UK, over 70 of which are from France.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:20:52.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573749/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573749/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573749/answer/previousversion/9617","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many child refugees have been assisted to enter the UK in the past year (a) in total and (b) who have come from Calais to join family living in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","44615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573750","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce additional pathways for refugees to come to the UK. The UK is already a leading resettlement state, offering a number of safe and legal pathways for refugees. In the year ending June 2016, a total of 3,439 people were resettled in the UK.</p><p>In addition to the 20,000 Syrian refugees and up to 3,000 vulnerable persons from the Middle East and North Africa region that the Government has committed to resettle by 2020, the UK has also committed to relocate unaccompanied refugee children from France, Greece and Italy. Under the family reunion policy we have reunited around 22,000 refugees with their immediate family over the past five years and will continue to do so. The Government supports the principle that those who need international protection should claim asylum in the first safe country they reach. This allows vulnerable persons to receive help quickly rather than risking their lives on hazardous journeys into and across Europe or falling victim to criminal gangs who are exploiting the situation. Providing humanitarian aid in the region is the best way to provide much needed support to the majority of those fleeing persecution while working with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to resettle the most vulnerable who cannot reasonably remain.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-08T14:42:31.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573750/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573750/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573750/answer/previousversion/9619","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to review the Government's commitments on the number of refugees to be granted access to the UK at the UN General Assembly Summit on Refugees and Migrants in September 2016.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","44583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573751","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>Since the beginning of this year, over 120 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in Europe have been accepted for transfer to the UK, over 70 of which are from France. The Government does not routinely publish statistics on the number of take charge requests accepted for unaccompanied asylum-seeking children transferring to the UK under the Dublin III regulation broken down by country or region.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:22:38.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573751/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573751/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573751/answer/previousversion/9601","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many unaccompanied minors have had their take charge request accepted in (a) Calais, (b) Greece and (c) Italy in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","44589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573752","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>For unaccompanied refugee children accepted for transfer to the UK, transfer requests are generally processed within 10 days and children transferred within weeks. However transfer arrangements are set by the transferring member state who have six months to do so under the III Dublin Regulations.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:23:04.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573752/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573752/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573752/answer/previousversion/9604","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time was for the family reunification process to be completed in (a) Calais, (b) Greece and (c) Italy in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","44592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573753","Home Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>There have been no changes in the requirements for European nationals entering or currently residing in the UK, nor of British citizens elsewhere in the EU. The precise way in which these requirements may change following the UK’s exit from the EU is yet to be determined.</p><p>The UK’s visa operation is resourced to meet demand, and we will ensure that any operational implications of the UK’s exit from the EU are fully factored into business planning.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-15T14:41:46.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573753/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573753/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that there is not a backlog of visa applications after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","44575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573754","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Home Department receives regular performance updates from the SIA, including information around the processing of licence applications. In the last financial year the SIA met its performance target for processing licence applications. We are however aware of some delays in the issuing of SIA licences following the launch of its new IT system in July 2016. The SIA have introduced a series of measures to address the issues and we will continue to monitor its performance in this area.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-07T13:31:33.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573754/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573754/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Security Guards: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Security Industry Authority's processing of license applications.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","44366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573755","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We operate several resettlement schemes that provide safe and legal routes to the United Kingdom for the most vulnerable refugees, including Gateway, Mandate, the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme and the Vulnerable children at risk schemes. In addition, we support the principle of family unity and have several routes to enable refugees and their families to be reunited.</p><p>We are under no obligation to consider asylum claims lodged outside UK territory and it would not be appropriate to do so. Those who need international protection should claim asylum in the first safe country they reach – that is the fastest route to safety.</p><p>We believe that seeking protection in the first safe country allows vulnerable people to receive help more quickly rather than risking their lives on hazardous journeys into and across Europe or falling victim to criminal gangs who are exploiting the situation. Providing humanitarian support in the region and working with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees on resettlement programmes remains the best way to provide much needed support to the majority of those facing persecution who remain in the region.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:45:46.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573755/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573755/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her policy is on allowing more refugees the opportunity to reach the UK safely and legally.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573756","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>This information is not held on Home Office systems.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-07T15:57:46.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573756/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573756/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Begging and Vagrancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many border staff were employed exclusively on checking the immigration status of beggars in (a) Westminster and (b) the UK; and how many of those checked were (i) illegal immigrants, (ii) committing criminal acts and (iii) deported in each of the last six months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","44225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573757","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We support the principle of family unity and have several routes for families to be reunited safely. Our family reunion policy allows a spouse or partner and children under the age of 18 of those granted protection in the UK to join them here, if they formed part of the family unit before the sponsor fled their country. Over the past five years we have granted over 22,000 family reunion visas and will continue to do so.</p><p>Where an application fails under the Immigration Rules, we consider whether there are exceptional or compassionate reasons for granting a visa outside the Rules. We published a revised Home Office policy on family reunion in July which provides further guidance for decision-makers on the types of case that may benefit from a grant of leave outside the Rules where there are exceptional circumstances.</p><p>This guidance is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/family-reunion-instruction.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:26:04.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573757/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573757/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department plans to do to increase the number of refugees reaching the UK safely and legally under the family reunification scheme.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573758","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We are considering potential changes to the UK passport after the UK has left the European Union. At this early stage we have not undertaken a detailed cost benefit analysis or made any decisions about what a future UK passport might look like.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T12:39:14.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573758/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573758/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has made an assessment of the potential costs and benefits of changing current UK passport types to the old blue style passport first issued in 1920.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","44321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573759","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-13","<p>Under the Animal Welfare Act 2006 animal fights, including dog fights, are prohibited. Offences include publicising a fight, providing information about an animal fight and betting on an animal fight. The maximum penalty for such offences is six months’ imprisonment, an unlimited fine or both. In addition, under section 1 of the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 four types of dog have been prohibited that are have been identified either as being bred for fighting or that share the characteristics of dogs bred for fighting. The maximum penalty for possession of an illegal type dog is six months’ imprisonment, an unlimited fine or both. Separately the independent Sentencing Council have recently consulted on changes to their guidelines to magistrates’ courts for a range of offences including animal cruelty offences. The Sentencing Council stated in June that in relation to animal cruelty, the Council wants to ensure that the most serious cases lead to prison sentences, and that these sentences are of an appropriate length.</p><p>The Government has also worked with the Pet Advertising Advisory Group (PAAG), a grouping of welfare charities and pet industry interests, who have been lobbying operators of internet sites to adopt minimum standards for the advertising of pet animals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-09-13T10:38:08.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573759/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573759/answer",,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-02","Dog Fighting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the incidence of illegal dog fighting.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","44317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573760","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Gangmasters Licensing Authority’s budget has seen an increase in 2016-17 to reflect its changing and broader functions. The budget has been published on page 80 of the Main Supply Estimate 2016-17. We remain committed to resourcing the GLA and continue to work with GLA to ensure it can deliver its purpose of protecting vulnerable and exploited workers in future years. The budget for GLA will be confirmed as part of the Main Estimate Supply exercise ahead of each financial year.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-09-08T14:45:21.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573760/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573760/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 5 July 2016 to Question 41352, (a) by how much and (b) from what date the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority's funding will be increased.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","44295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573761","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>HM Government will be represented at the UN General Assembly high level meeting on 19 September and the Leaders’ Summit on refugees to be hosted by President Obama on 20 September.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T12:39:01.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573761/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573761/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to attend the UN General Assembly meetings on refugees and migrants on 19 and 20 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573762","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>Information on how many former overseas students of the Cambridge College of Learning would have submitted an indefinite leave to remain or UK citizenship application is not aggregated in national reporting systems. This information could only be obtained by a manual case by case review to collate the data, which would be disproportionately expensive.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-07T15:05:55.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573762/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573762/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many former overseas students of the Cambridge College of Learning have been granted (a) indefinite leave to remain and (b) UK citizenship since that College's closure.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","44372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573763","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>The information is not readily available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>We are able to identify seizures of stun weapons from our last data sets, but can not easily identify those which have been disguised. In order to obtain this information, we would have to examine individual records to establish which stun guns were disguised.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-07T15:55:40.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573763/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573763/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Smuggling: Stun Guns","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many disguised stun weapons have been seized at the UK border in each year since 2011-12.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","44370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573764","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Home Office’s database that is used to record sponsorship data was introduced after the Cambridge College of Learning closed down.</p><p>We are, therefore, unable to obtain details of the college’s former overseas students.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-07T15:56:57.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573764/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573764/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many former overseas students of the Cambridge College of Learning were (a) deported and (b) not deported following that College's closure.","false","Biography information for Dominic Raab","Esher and Walton","Mr Dominic Raab","44371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573765","Home Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>Between 1st January and 30th June 2016, 110 removals of people who have previously been refused asylum and had their claims certified, took place. Of those claimants removed in that period four lodged appeals; there were no successful appeals by the end of the same period.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-13T12:14:07.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573765/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573765/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573765/answer/previousversion/9613","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people refused asylum under the non-suspensive appeal policy were removed from the UK in the first six months of 2016; and how many such people (a) lodged an appeal and (b) successfully appealed against the refusal of their asylum application.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","44205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573766","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Prime Minister has announced £33.5 million of Official Development Assistance (ODA) funding over five years. The fund be will be used to prevent slavery in ODA eligible countries and bring perpetratorsto justice; helping communities to fight modern slavery. We have already announced that:</p><p>• The Commonwealth Parliamentary Association UK has been funded to work with parliaments across the Commonwealth to support them in considering legislation similar to the UK’s world-leading Modern Slavery Act 2015.</p><p>• £2.4 million has been allocated to the £3 million Child Trafficking Protection Fund.</p><p>Some funding will be used to support innovative programmes to reduce the prevalence of modern slavery and improve the evidence base on what works. A call for proposals on the innovation fund will be issued later this year.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-09-08T14:44:16.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573766/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573766/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573766/answer/previousversion/9616","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/members/4071","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","International Modern Slavery Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) specific functions and (b) scope of the recently established International Modern Slavery Fund will be.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","44226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573767","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>This issue was considered in detail by an expert group comprising representatives of law enforcement, the security and intelligence agencies and communication service providers following the terrorist attacks in London in July 2005. The experts’ findings remain valid. They concluded that the registration of ownership of mobile telephones would not deliver any significant new benefits to the investigatory process.</p><p>Mobile phones are not the only devices capable of making calls or sending messages. Many laptops, computers, popular MP3 players and games consoles also support the sending of messages and phone calls. These devices are increasingly being used for communications. It would be necessary to include these other devices in any mandatory registration scheme.</p><p>Separately, the person who buys the device is not necessarily the person who will use it. Mobile phones are often sold or given to family members or friends which would mean that such information would quickly become out of date.</p><p>Furthermore, those who were keen to avoid providing details would still find ways to circumvent the scheme, such as purchasing or registering phones under false identities.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-09-07T16:45:01.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573767/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573767/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573767/answer/previousversion/9626","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/members/4071","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Mobile Phones: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the (a) potential benefits to security and (b) viability of effective implementation of requiring proof of identification prior to purchase of a SIM card.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","44233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573768","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>In the first six months of 2016, our records indicate that the UK has returned 198 applicants to other Member States under the Dublin III Regulations to have their asylum applications considered.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T12:35:59.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573768/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573768/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573768/answer/previousversion/9614","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum applications have been transferred to another EU country under the Dublin III Regulation in the first six months of 2016.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","44218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573769","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>Following the referendum, internal structures have beeen put in place to coordinate the Home Office’s contribution to UK’s exit from the EU.</p><p>The Home Office International Directorate is coordinating the Home Office’s approach both to ongoing EU business and the forthcoming UK exit negotiations. Alongside this work, the Home Office will continue to work with the Department for Exiting the EU in reaching the best deal for Britain.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:27:06.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573769/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573769/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps her Department plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573770","Department for Education","false","2016-09-14","<p>Funding for English for Speakers of Other Languages is not ring-fenced but forms part of the Adult Education Budget (AEB). Providers will use their AEB allocation to put on appropriate provision based on their judgement of the economic and social needs of their local area. We expect that this will include ESOL where there is significant demand.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government has pledged up to £10 million over five years for a jointly funded DfE and Home Office programme to enable Syrian refugees across the UK to access language tuition and integrate into British society.</p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-09-14T16:24:53.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573770/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573770/answer",,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-02","English Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the annual funding from the public purse is for English Speakers of Other Languages schemes.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","44172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573771","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>No information is recorded in national reporting systems to enable reporting on the time taken to process reconsideration requests for rejected applications for British naturalisation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T12:38:24.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573771/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573771/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Naturalisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time taken is to process reconsideration requests for rejected applications for British naturalisation.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573772","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government began work to implement the ‘Dubs amendment’ immediately after the Immigration Bill gained Royal Assent. Over 30 children who meet the criteria in the Immigration Act have been accepted for transfer since it received Royal Assent in May, the majority of these have already arrived in the UK.</p><p>We continue to work with the French, Greek and Italian authorities and others to speed up existing family reunification processes or implement new processes where necessary for unaccompanied children. We have seconded a UK official to Greece, we have a long-standing secondee working in Italy and will shortly be seconding another official to the French Interior Ministry to support these efforts.</p><p>We have established a dedicated team in the Home Office Dublin Unit to lead on family reunion cases for unaccompanied children. Transfer requests under the Dublin Regulation are now generally processed within 10 days and children transferred within weeks. Over 120 children have been accepted for transfer this year from Europe. We also continue to consult local authorities about the transfer unaccompanied refugee children from Europe to the UK, where it is in their best interests.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T16:15:17.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573772/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573772/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to speed up family reunification for unaccompanied refugee children in Europe.","false","Biography information for Alex Salmond","Gordon","Alex Salmond","44426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573773","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Home Office has not received any representations regarding the appointment of Sir John Chadwick to head the independent inquiry into the mistreatment of live foxes by the South Herefordshire Hunt.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-08T10:36:58.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573773/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573773/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Animal Welfare: Foxes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations her Department has received on alleged conflicts of interest in the appointment of Sir John Chadwick to head an inquiry into the mistreatment of live foxes by the South Herefordshire Hunt.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","44448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573774","Home Office","false","2016-09-09","<p>The table below gives the number of individuals who were successfully prosecuted by Home Office Immigration Enforcement for offences relating to immigration marriage fraud.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Successfully prosecuted</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>121</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>37</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Prior to 2014, the records were not held centrally.</p><p>The decrease in the number of referrals to the Home Office can be aligned to the introduction of the Immigration Act 2014.</p><p>This legislation extends the notification period for those seeking to marry up to 70 days and provides time for the Home Office to investigate whether the marriage is sham. The effect of this is that those marriages deemed to be sham can be prevented from taking place.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-09T16:21:46.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573774/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573774/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Marriage of Convenience: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many convictions there have been for offences relating to cases of immigration marriage fraud in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","44438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573775","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>We know that the majority of forces in England and Wales use Body Worn Video (BWV) to some extent. The deployment of BWV is an operational decision for chief officers. However, we are aware that West Yorkshire Police are operating a phased rollout of body worn video cameras to frontline officers following an initial pilot, with officers in the Bradford and Calderdale districts already equipped.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-09-07T15:06:29.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573775/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573775/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress the West Yorkshire police force has made on piloting and evaluating the use by police officers of body-worn cameras.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","44439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573776","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Home Office works closely with local authorities to support resettled refugees as they arrive in their areas. Local authorities have a duty to protect individuals in their care – this includes resettled Syrians.</p><p>The Care Act 2014 put adult safeguarding on a legal footing and established that each local authority must set up Adult Safeguarding Boards with multi-agency membership including local partners and the Police. Local agencies, including the police and health services, also have a duty under section 11 of the Children Act 2004 to ensure that they consider the need to safeguard and promote the welfare of children when carrying out their functions.</p><p>In addition, upon arrival, the local authority assign a caseworker to every resettled family/individual, who maintains close contact with the family for the first 12 months to support their well being and integration. The small number of unaccompanied minors being resettled will be placed into local authority care where their safety needs, along with other needs, will be met via the resettling authority’s children’s social care service.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-07T15:06:12.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573776/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573776/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure the safety of refugees coming to the UK.","false","Biography information for Alex Salmond","Gordon","Alex Salmond","44390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573777","Home Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce additional pathways for refugees to come to the UK. The UK is already a leading resettlement state, offering a number of safe and legal pathways for refugees. In the year ending June 2016, a total of 3,439 people were resettled in the UK.</p><p>In addition to the 20,000 Syrian refugees and up to 3,000 vulnerable persons from the Middle East and North Africa region that the Government has committed to resettle by 2020, the UK has also committed to relocate unaccompanied refugee children from France, Greece and Italy. Under the family reunion policy we have reunited around 22,000 refugees with their immediate family over the past five years and will continue to do so. The Government supports the principle that those who need international protection should claim asylum in the first safe country they reach. This allows vulnerable persons to receive help quickly rather than risking their lives on hazardous journeys into and across Europe or falling victim to criminal gangs who are exploiting the situation. Providing humanitarian aid in the region is the best way to provide much needed support to the majority of those fleeing persecution while working with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to resettle the most vulnerable who cannot reasonably remain.</p><p>HM Government will be represented at the UN General Assembly high level meeting on 19 September and the Leaders’ Summit on refugees to be hosted by President Obama on 20 September.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","44526","2016-09-08T14:40:26.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573777/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573777/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573777/answer/previousversion/9623","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to make a commitment at the UN Summit for Refugees and Migrants on 19 and 20 September 2016 to provide more safe and legal routes for refugees to find protection in the UK.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","44525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573778","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government began work to implement the ‘Dubs amendment’ immediately after the Immigration Bill gained Royal Assent. Over 30 children who meet the criteria in the Immigration Act have been accepted for transfer since it received Royal Assent in May, the majority of these have already arrived in the UK.</p><p>We continue to work with the French, Greek and Italian authorities and others to speed up existing family reunification processes or implement new processes where necessary for unaccompanied children. We have seconded a UK official to Greece, we have a long-standing secondee working in Italy and will shortly be seconding another official to the French Interior Ministry to support these efforts.</p><p>We have established a dedicated team in the Home Office Dublin Unit to lead on family reunion cases for unaccompanied children. Transfer requests under the Dublin Regulation are now generally processed within 10 days and children transferred within weeks. Over 120 children have been accepted for transfer this year from Europe. We also continue to consult local authorities about the transfer unaccompanied refugee children from Europe to the UK, where it is in their best interests.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T12:36:32.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573778/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573778/answer","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573778/answer/previousversion/9612","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/members/1562","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to accelerate family reunification for unaccompanied refugee children in Europe.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","44534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573779","Home Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>The report recommends that the cash allowance provided to destitute asylum seekers, currently set at £36.95 per week, is raised. The level of the allowance is reviewed regularly to ensure that it is sufficient to cover essential living needs of individual asylum seekers and we will announce the result of this year’s review later this year.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-07T15:00:29.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573779/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573779/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Asylum: Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to respond to the concluding observations and recommendations of the UN Committee on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights on the UK's sixth periodic report in relation to welfare support for asylum-seekers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","44398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573780","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>COMPASS accommodation providers, including Serco, are contractually required to provide safe, habitable, fit for purpose and correctly equipped accommodation to comply with the standards outlined in the relevant housing legislation and the Decent Homes Standard.</p><p>The Government expects the highest standards from our contractors and providers are monitored closely to ensure asylum accommodation providers meet these standards. Where a contractor is found to be falling short of these standards, we work with them to ensure issues are quickly addressed. When they are not we can and do impose sanctions.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:52:43.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573780/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573780/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the suitability and adequacy of conduct of landlords engaged by Serco and its subcontractors to provide accommodation to refugees and asylum seekers under the COMPASS contract.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","44407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573781","Home Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Home Office works closely with COMPASS providers and local authorities through Strategic Migration Partnerships to plan for the most appropriate dispersal of asylum seekers.</p><p>These partnerships allow Providers to formally consult with local authorities and statutory bodies to ensure all new proposed property procurement and landlords meet the required contractual and statutory standards.</p><p>Any Local Authority that has concerns about the suitability or conduct of individual landlords can raise this with the Home Office and COMPASS providers either directly or through the Strategic Migration Partnerships.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-09-12T15:52:32.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573781/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573781/answer",,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-02","Compass Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what consultation and contact her Department has undertaken with local authorities on the suitability and conduct of landlords engaged by Serco and its subcontractors to provide accommodation to refugees and asylum seekers under the COMPASS contract.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","44406"
