><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>S.72(3) &amp; S 72(1) (8)Valueadded Tax Act 1994</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(2) The figures given in the table on court proceedings relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p>(3) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-30T09:33:25.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573796/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573796/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been sentenced to a term in prison for (a) non-payment of council tax, (b) watching television broadcasts without a television licence and (c) tax evasion in each year from 2008-09 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","44494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573797","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>The National Offender Management Service (NOMS) is committed to ensuring the health, safety and wellbeing of its staff.</p><p> </p><p>An employee’s GP retains primary responsibility for the care and treatment of mental health problems. NOMS recognises its duty of care to staff and provides wide ranging occupational health services, fast tracking to psychological interventions (where clinically indicated for ill-health due to work related trauma), and offers comprehensive employee assistance (EAP) services which are available 24 hours a day, 365 days a year in support. Staff are also able to self-refer for counselling by calling a 24 hour helpline in complete confidentiality. A well-established system of Care Teams also exists which provide the social and practical support for staff in the early days following a serious incident.</p><p> </p><p>Innovations and support locally are continually under review and enhanced wherever possible. Assessment of the adequacy of support is ongoing at all levels – locally, regionally, and nationally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-12T14:20:40.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573797/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573797/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Prison Officers: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of support available to prison officers experiencing mental illness.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","44550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573798","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>We will publish the outcome of our review into Employment Tribunal Fees in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-12T15:43:30.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573798/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573798/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to publish the report of her Department's implementation review of employment tribunal fees which was initiated on 11 June 2015.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","44544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573799","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-13","<p>Approved Premises (formerly known as probation or bail hostels) are used to provide enhanced supervision for higher-risk offenders who have been released from prison after completing the custodial part of their sentence. They also house a small number of defendants on bail. My Department is analysing the capacity and distribution of the Approved Premises estate to establish whether more places are needed.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-13T16:29:05.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573799/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573799/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Approved Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if her Department will make an assessment of the potential merits of increasing the number of offenders on probation housed in Approved Premises.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","44557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573800","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-15","<p>Actions in the VAWG Action Plan are monitored through the VAWG Delivery Board, the VAWG Inter Ministerial Group and bilateral meetings between Home Office and OGD officials.</p><p> </p><p>The VAWG Stakeholder Meeting is a meeting between Home Office officials and attendees from the voluntary and community sector working in the violence against women and girls policy area. It is not routinely attended by officials from other government departments. The most recent meeting took place on July 11. While OGDs do not routinely attend, as this meeting is primarily between the Home Office and the sector, an action point raised by the sector at this meeting was their desire for other Government departments to be represented at future meetings. This will be taken forward by the Home Office by inviting OGD officials to future meetings.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-09-15T16:00:22.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573800/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573800/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Ministry of Justice: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department is taking to implement the actions identified for it in the Government's Ending Violence against Women and Girls Strategy 2016-2020, published in March 2016; and when a member of staff from her Department last attended a Violence against Women and Girls Stakeholder Meeting chaired by the Home Office.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","44237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573801","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>100 Approved Premises have been operational since 2010. Figures on the number of individuals who have resided in each of the Approved Premises are not held centrally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-12T14:45:47.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573801/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573801/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Approved Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) Approved Premises have been operational and (b) people have resided in each of those premises in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","44270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573802","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>Offenders required to reside in Approved Premises are entitled to the same health provision as ordinary members of the public.</p><p>Approved Premises staff are not medically qualified and so cannot give clinical advice. They do have a general duty of care and Approved Premises staff are trained in identifying and working with people with addictions or mental health problems. All residents are obliged to be registered with a GP, and many Approved Premises have arranged provision such as on-site GP attendance and run healthy living programmes.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-12T10:23:47.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573802/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573802/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Approved Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what advice her Department provides to people living in Approved Premises who have (a) an addiction, (b) a mental health condition and (c) other health conditions.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","44271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573803","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister. In doing this it is working very closely with other government departments, including the Ministry of Justice, and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-12T15:28:24.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573803/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573803/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps her Department plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573804","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>A life sentence is mandatory for murder. A life sentence must also be imposed for a second, very serious, specified violent or sexual offence – for example, manslaughter, GBH with intent, rape, and sexual assault on a child under 13 - unless the court finds that there are particular circumstances relating to the offence or the offender which would make it unjust to do so.</p><p> </p><p>Under a life sentence, the offender must serve the full minimum term imposed by the court before being considered for release on life licence by the Parole Board, which will only release an offender if and when it considers it safe to do so. Where a whole life order is imposed the offender is not eligible for parole.</p><p> </p><p>The number of life sentences imposed in each of the last ten years can be found on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","44442","2016-09-12T14:26:20.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573804/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573804/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Life Imprisonment: Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners serving a mandatory life sentence have been released early from prison in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","44441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573805","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>A life sentence is mandatory for murder. A life sentence must also be imposed for a second, very serious, specified violent or sexual offence – for example, manslaughter, GBH with intent, rape, and sexual assault on a child under 13 - unless the court finds that there are particular circumstances relating to the offence or the offender which would make it unjust to do so.</p><p> </p><p>Under a life sentence, the offender must serve the full minimum term imposed by the court before being considered for release on life licence by the Parole Board, which will only release an offender if and when it considers it safe to do so. Where a whole life order is imposed the offender is not eligible for parole.</p><p> </p><p>The number of life sentences imposed in each of the last ten years can be found on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","44441","2016-09-12T14:26:20.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573805/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573805/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Life Imprisonment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have been handed a life sentence in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","44442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573806","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Ministry continues to be in regular contact with G4S and other relevant bodies. This engagement includes monitoring the progress of the potential sale to ensure it does not jeopardise the delivery of services at the Secure Training Centres<strong>. </strong></p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-09-13T13:02:48.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573806/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573806/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Oakhill Secure Training Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress has been made on the sale of the contract for Oakhill secure training centre.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","44427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573807","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Offender Rehabilitation Act was a key piece of legislation under the Transforming Rehabilitation Programme that extended statutory rehabilitation to offenders who served short sentences. Time spent on licence is an integral part of a custodial sentence. It is right that all offenders under probation supervision are subject to strict monitoring. In some cases offenders are recalled if their behaviour is causing concern to prevent a further offence from being committed.</p><p> </p><p>In order to enable prisons to deliver the requirements of the act the National Offender Management Service reviewed resources within each prison establishment Offender Management Units that received remand prisoners. Following this review additional roles were introduced across prison establishments to support the increased casework processes.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-12T14:32:16.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573807/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573807/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what additional resources were made available to prisons to accommodate the increased number of people recalled to custody following the introduction of the Offender Rehabilitation Act 2014.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","44428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573808","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>There are several agencies involved in recalling and returning offenders to custody. The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-12T10:56:51.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573808/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573808/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the cost of recalling 22,412 people to custody over the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","44429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573809","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>The UN requested that the UK submits its next periodic report under the Covenant (inclusive of a response to all the recommendations from this year’s examination) by 30 June 2021; it would therefore not be appropriate for me to pre-empt this report by anticipating what we, or indeed a future UK Government in 2021, might say.</p><p> </p><p>We regularly monitor the operation of the legal aid scheme on an ongoing basis. The Legal Aid Agency routinely collects data on the age, sex, disability status and ethnicity of recipients of legal aid and publishes statistics on this topic annually. We have committed to carrying out a Post Implementation Review, which will consider the impact of the legal aid provisions in the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 on access to justice. The UK Government is also currently undertaking a review of the introduction of fees into the Employment Tribunals and will publish its findings in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-12T15:41:52.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573809/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573809/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she plans to respond to the concluding observations and recommendations of the UN Committee on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights on the UK's sixth periodic report in relation to legal aid and access to justice; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","44410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573810","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) does not hold accurate information on the volumes of appeals against decisions on claims for Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) and Personal Independence Payment (PIP). At the point of receipt and registration of the appeal the Tribunal is unable to differentiate between appeals relating to new claims for these benefits and those relating to existing claims.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the volumes and outcomes of appeals to the Tribunal is published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</a>. The information provided below is a further breakdown of this data (excluding reassessment decisions).</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>ESA appeals (excluding reassessment decisions) found in favour of the appellant </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock</strong><strong><sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p>775</p></td><td><p>845</p></td><td><p>1073</p></td><td><p>271</p></td><td><p>221</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>UK </strong></p></td><td><p>62147</p></td><td><p>56042</p></td><td><p>88946</p></td><td><p>24979</p></td><td><p>25831</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>PIP </strong><strong><sup>2</sup></strong><strong> appeals (excluding reassessment decisions) found in favour of the appellant</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>176</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>UK</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>3374</p></td><td><p>20659</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup> Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock may be represented by the venues at Ayr, Dumfries, Irvine, Kilmarnock and Stranraer. Social Security and Child Support data are attributed according to the venue nearest the appellant’s home address. HMCTS cannot retrieve data based on the appellant’s actual address, or Parliamentary constituency, but can produce data detailing numbers of cases dealt with at regional centres, or at a specific venue.</p><p> </p><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system</p><p> </p><p><sup>2 </sup>PIP was introduced as a new benefit in April 2013 to replace Disability Living Allowance (DLA) for people aged 16 to 64, and appeal volumes have been rising ever since its introduction. In addition to new claims for PIP, the Department for Work and Pensions is also transitioning individuals in receipt of DLA, over to PIP, via a reassessment programme.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-12T15:37:12.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573810/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573810/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many decisions taken on claims for (a) employment and support allowance and (b) personal independence payment have been appealed in (i) Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock and (ii) the UK in each of the last five years; and how many of those appeals have been successful.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","44405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573811","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Justice Secretary is clear that safety is fundamental to the proper functioning of our justice system and a vital part of our reform plans. There are a number of factors, including the availability of drugs in prisons, which must be tackled in order to make our prisons safe and places of rehabilitation.</p><p> </p><p>We have introduced tough new laws which will see those who smuggle packages over prison walls, including new psychoactive substances, face up to two years in prison. Those who involve themselves in the distribution of drugs in our prisons should know that they could face prosecution and extra time behind bars. We have a range of security measures and searching techniques in place to detect drugs, and to prevent smuggling into prisons.</p><p> </p><p>I am looking closely at this important issue, and will be setting our further plans in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","44844","2016-09-12T14:42:06.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573811/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573811/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the level of drugs in prisons.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","44392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573812","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>Information about the numbers of special educational needs and disability tribunals is published by the Ministry of Justice in the Tribunals and Gender Recognition Statistics Quarterly on gov.uk</p><p> </p><p>Information about the total cost to the public purse of defending the refusal to issue special educational statements each year since 2010 is not held centrally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-12T15:31:28.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573812/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573812/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Special Educational Needs: Tribunals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many special educational needs and disability tribunals there have been in each year since 2010; and what the total cost to the public purse of defending the refusal to issue special educational statements was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573813","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-12","<p>Ministry of Justice records show that there were no secondments to the Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-09-12T11:17:32.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573813/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573813/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Ministry of Justice: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will publish a list of all secondees to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573814","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-13","<p>It has not been possible to answer this question in the time allowed. I will write to the right honourable member in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-09-13T16:21:33.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573814/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573814/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Ministry of Justice: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times her Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573815","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-07","<p>HM Inspectorate of Prisons’ report on HMP Chelmsford was published on 16 August this year. We take all recommendations made by the Chief Inspector seriously and the prison is taking action to address the Chief Inspector’s findings. We will produce a detailed action plan within three months responding to all the recommendations in the report. The action plan will be published on the Inspectorate’s web site.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-07T16:38:01.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573815/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573815/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Chelmsford Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she plans to take in response to the most recent HM Inspectorate of Prisons report on HMP Chelmsford; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Simon Burns","Chelmsford","Sir Simon Burns","44527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573816","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-07","<p>We are carefully considering the responses to our earlier consultation on this issue, and will set out further plans in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","44515 ; 44516","2016-09-07T16:22:41.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573816/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573816/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Probate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what safeguards her Department is providing to enable applications to be filed for Grants of Probate in respect of Estates which do not have sufficient liquid funds to pay fees to Probate Registries.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","44514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573817","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-07","<p>We are carefully considering the responses to our earlier consultation on this issue, and will set out further plans in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","44514 ; 44516","2016-09-07T16:22:41.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573817/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573817/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Probate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the recent proposals to allow Probate Registries to collect fees will reflect the actual cost of administration of the Probate Registries; and whether her Department plans that those fees will more accurately reflect the amount of time expended by staff in the Probate Registries.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","44515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573818","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-07","<p>We are carefully considering the responses to our earlier consultation on this issue, and will set out further plans in due course.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","44514 ; 44515","2016-09-07T16:22:41.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573818/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573818/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Probate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether her Department plans that the recent proposals to allow Probate Registries to collect fees will (a) produce a surplus for the Department's income and expenditure and (b) subsidise HM Courts and Tribunals Service.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","44516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573819","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-07","<p>We have made sure that legal aid continues to be available in the most serious cases, for example where people’s life, liberty, or housing is at stake or where their children may be taken into care. The operation of, and expenditure on, the legal aid scheme is continually monitored by the Ministry of Justice and the Legal Aid Agency.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-09-07T16:28:08.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573819/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573819/answer",,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-09-02","Administration of Justice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what monitoring her Department has carried out to ensure that no one is denied access to justice, regardless of ability to pay for legal representation.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","44521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573820","Leader of the House","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister. In doing this it is working very closely with other government departments, including the Office of the Leader of the House of Commons, and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-09-09T09:34:22.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573820/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573820/answer",,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-09-02","Leader of the House of Commons: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what steps his Office has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps his Office plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573821","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister.</p><p>In doing this it is working very closely with other government departments, including the Northern Ireland Office, and a wide range of other interested parties.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-09-09T10:11:10.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573821/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573821/answer",,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-09-02","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps his Department plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573822","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland has regular discussions with colleagues on a range of issues regarding the UK’s exit from the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer confirmed on 13 August that European Structural and Investment Funds (ESIFs) projects signed before the Autumn Statement will be fully funded, even when these projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>For projects signed after the Autumn Statement, the Government will work with the devolved administrations on funding arrangements to allow them to prioritise projects within their devolved responsibilities. As we transition to longer-term arrangements, we will ensure the devolved administrations are treated fairly and that their circumstances are taken into account.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","44787","2016-09-12T14:38:41.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573822/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573822/answer",,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-09-02","Disability: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions he has had on maintaining the level of funding for disabled people in Northern Ireland when support for such people from the European Social Fund ceases.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","44171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573823","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-09-09","<p>The cost of extending the digital registration service to Northern Ireland is being met by the Cabinet Office as part of the wider project to implement digital registration throughout the UK.</p><p>This work is ongoing and the current estimate of costs is approximately £250,000.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-09-09T10:12:25.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573823/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573823/answer",,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-09-02","Electoral Register: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the estimated cost to the public purse is of implementing online voter registration in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","44178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573824","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Department has used the services of (a) PwC, once in the last three financial years. This was for the provision of VAT advice. The cost to the public purse was £1,350. My department has not used the services of any other consultant firms in the last three financial years.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-09-08T10:34:59.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573824/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573824/answer",,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-09-02","Northern Ireland Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many times his Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573825","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Northern Ireland Office has not had any secondees from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-09-08T10:35:56.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573825/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573825/answer",,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-09-02","Northern Ireland Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if he will publish a list of all secondees to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573826","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>Information relating to specific pieces of work undertaken by all consulting firms including details of secondments from consulting firms is not held centrally and is therefore only available at disproportionate cost. In May 2010 the Cabinet Office introduced a control on the use of consultants within central government to reduce spending and to challenge organisations to only use consultants when absolutely necessary. Details of expenditure approvals for consultancy controls are published on: <a href="http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk</a> and on <a href="http://data.gov.uk/" target="_blank">data.gov.uk</a>: <a href="http://www.data.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.data.gov.uk</a> Additionally, all new contracts over the value of £10,000 and payments of over £25,000 are published on Contracts Finder: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a> Under the Government controls introduced in May 2010, any contract for consultancy the estimated value of which exceeds £20,000 and exceeds 9 months in duration must be approved by the MCO and the Chief Secretary to the Treasury. Any consultancy contracts that fall outside of this scope must be approved by Cabinet Office Finance as part of the standard departmental financial controls. The full Cabinet Office Controls guidance can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-controls/cabinet-office-controls-guidance-version-40" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-controls/cabinet-office-controls-guidance-version-40</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","44324 ; 44337 ; 44344","2016-09-08T08:53:57.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573826/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573826/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-02","Prime Minister: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many times his Office has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573827","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>Information relating to specific pieces of work undertaken by all consulting firms including details of secondments from consulting firms is not held centrally and is therefore only available at disproportionate cost. In May 2010 the Cabinet Office introduced a control on the use of consultants within central government to reduce spending and to challenge organisations to only use consultants when absolutely necessary. Details of expenditure approvals for consultancy controls are published on: <a href="http://www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk</a> and on <a href="http://data.gov.uk/" target="_blank">data.gov.uk</a>: <a href="http://www.data.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.data.gov.uk</a> Additionally, all new contracts over the value of £10,000 and payments of over £25,000 are published on Contracts Finder: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a> Under the Government controls introduced in May 2010, any contract for consultancy the estimated value of which exceeds £20,000 and exceeds 9 months in duration must be approved by the MCO and the Chief Secretary to the Treasury. Any consultancy contracts that fall outside of this scope must be approved by Cabinet Office Finance as part of the standard departmental financial controls. The full Cabinet Office Controls guidance can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-controls/cabinet-office-controls-guidance-version-40" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-controls/cabinet-office-controls-guidance-version-40</a></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","44324 ; 44344 ; 44357","2016-09-08T08:53:57.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573827/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573827/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-02","Prime Minister: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish a list of all secondees to his Office from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573828","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-07","<p>Information on budgets for new departments, including budgets allocated for the creation of the department, will be held by the departments in question. Budgets for new departments will be voted on by Parliament at the Supplementary Estimate.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-09-07T08:42:50.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573828/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573828/answer",,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-02","Government Departments: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to his Written Ministerial Statement of 18 July 2016 on Machinery of Government Changes, HCWS94, if he will publish data setting out all costs associated with the changes outlined in that statement.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","44179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573829","Prime Minister","false","2016-09-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Oral Statement I gave to the House on 7 September 2016, <em>Official Report</em>, column 336.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-09-09T12:08:24.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573829/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573829/answer",,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-09-02","Prime Minister: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what steps 10 Downing Street has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps 10 Downing Street plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573830","Prime Minister","false","2016-09-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Oral Statement I gave to the House on 7 September 2016, <em>Official Report</em>, column 336.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-09-09T12:09:27.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573830/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573830/answer",,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-09-02","UN Refugees and Migrants Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she plans to attend the UN General Assembly meetings on refugees and migrants on 19 and 20 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573831","Scotland Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister.</p><p>In doing this, it is working very closely with other government departments, including the Scotland Office, the devolved administrations and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-09-08T10:26:51.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573831/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573831/answer",,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-09-02","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps his Department plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573832","Scotland Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>In the last three financial years, there have been no secondees at the Scotland Office from PwC, Deloitte, Ernst and Young, KPMG or any other consulting firms.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-09-08T10:28:01.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573832/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573832/answer",,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-09-02","Scotland Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will publish a list of all secondees to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573833","Scotland Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Scotland Office has not used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-09-08T10:29:19.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573833/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573833/answer",,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-09-02","Scotland Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many times his Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573834","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>To provide the detailed spend and purpose information requested on each individual occasion would require manual intervention and analysis on approximately 30,000 payments across the Department for Transport and its agencies. The number of times an organisation was used will also vary each year as projects can span financial years and this could lead to double counting with the risk that inaccurate information is provided. I am therefore unable to provide the information in the format requested.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T12:48:53.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573834/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573834/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Department for Transport: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many times his Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573835","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The total number of secondees to the Department from (a) PWC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years is 4.</p><p> </p><p>Due to the low number of secondees, we are unable to be more specific in the information so as to protect individuals from being identified personally.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T16:20:05.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573835/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573835/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Department for Transport: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish a list of all secondees to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573836","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-08","<p>Local authorities do not have powers to independently extend eligibility. The criteria are set by statutory instrument. The Disabled Persons (Badges for Motor Vehicles) (England) Regulations 2000 (as amended) contain a number of criteria covering those who do not qualify automatically, including a provision for <strong><em>any</em></strong> permanent and substantial disability that causes inability to walk or very considerable difficulty in walking. It is the responsibility of local authorities to assess whether applicants meet any of the criteria.</p><p> </p><p>People with autism are not excluded from being issued a badge. Any permanent and substantial disability that causes very considerable difficulty walking falls within the criteria. It is the responsibility of local authorities to assess the degree of difficulty and to issue badges accordingly. We have no plans to provide badges to carers.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","44292","2016-09-08T09:29:08.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573836/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573836/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Blue Badge Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what provisions are available to local authorities for extending the eligibility criteria for the Blue Badge scheme to people with severe physical disabilities who are not automatically eligible.","false","Biography information for Mary Robinson","Cheadle","Mary Robinson","44293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573837","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>There are only 8 existing municipal bus companies operating services in England and the Department does not currently have any plans to undertake analysis on the potential benefits of the municipal bus company model.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-09T09:40:32.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573837/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573837/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 29 February 2016 to Question 27306, if his Department will undertake analysis to understand the potential benefits for bus passengers of the municipal bus company model.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573838","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Prime Minister will begin the negotiation for Britain’s future relationship with Europe and will also take the decision about when to trigger article 50 and start the formal process of leaving the EU. The Prime Minister has been clear that article 50 will not be triggered before the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to delivering the important infrastructure projects the country needs, including delivering runway capacity on the timetable set out by the Airports Commission. The Government are giving high priority to this issue and the decision will be made shortly.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T14:10:45.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573838/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573838/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the likely impact of the result of the EU referendum on the timetable for a decision on Heathrow expansion.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","44381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573839","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>We have capped the rail fares we regulate at inflation (Retail Price Index) since 2014, and will continue to do so for the life of this parliament. This means those fares we regulate will not rise by more than1.9% in 2017. Limiting fares increases to inflation-only means that industry revenues keep track, but do not out-pace, the impact of inflation on their costs. Our current investment programme is the largest since the Victorian era and requires funding from both taxpayers and farepayers. As part of this, the GTR Franchise Agreement contains obligations requiring the franchisee to make significant improvements at stations and on trains through the life of the franchise. On the Thameslink network alone that means £1.6billion of new trains which started to be introduced earlier this summer and Gatwick Express has also benefited from new trains. During this time of major investment we are also clear that at the same time we must deliver a more joined up approach to running the trains and tracks and make things work better for the travelling public. That is why My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State has just announced a package of measure including a £20milion fund and the appointment of one of Britain’s most experienced rail industry figures to get the service running back as it should.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T15:30:17.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573839/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573839/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Govia Thameslink Railway: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans are in place for the proposed fare increase due on 1 January 2017 to directly fund improvements on the GTR network.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","44513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573840","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>I regret that due to pressures on my diary I will not be able to visit the Cumbrian Coast Rail Line in the near future. However, I will be writing to the Hon. Member to respond to the concerns he has raised with the Secretary of State about the progression of enhancements to the line to support proposed economic development in his constituency.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-09T10:54:26.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573840/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573840/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Railways: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will visit the Cumbrian Coast Rail Line between Carlisle and Whitehaven.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","44391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573841","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Government wants to see taxis and private hire vehicles prosper in London and elsewhere. The regulations issued by Transport for London are a matter for them as the local licensing authority. The legislation that provides for licensing of taxi and private hire vehicle services is enabling in its nature, giving local licensing authorities the discretion to set standards that they deem to be appropriate for their area.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-09T10:16:54.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573841/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573841/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Taxis: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will introduce new national regulations for private hire driver licences in line with Transport for London's new regulations for private hire drivers which will come into force on 1 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573842","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Secretary of State recently met with the Confederation of Passenger Transport and private bus operators to discuss the Bus Services Bill, which included discussion of Clause 21.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-09T11:03:00.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573842/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573842/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Bus Services Bill (HL)","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with private bus operators on Clause 21 of the Bus Services Bill.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573843","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Through Transport Focus, the Department has conducted three pieces of bus related research on contactless payments and smart ticketing:</p><p>a) Oxford SmartZone smart card evaluation - published in September 2013</p><p>b) Norfolk’s smart card evaluation - published in March 2015</p><p>c) Non-London bus passenger attitudes towards contactless payments - not yet published.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-12T09:34:07.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573843/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573843/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Bus Services: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research his Department has conducted on the potential effect of cashless payments and smart ticketing on buses on (a) bus journey times, (b) bus patronage and (c) congestion.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573844","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Department for Transport’s Best Practice Guidance on taxi and private hire licensing was issued in 2010. It is expected that a consultation on revised guidance will be launched early next year. Subject to Royal Assent to the Policing and Crime Bill, this will be accompanied by draft Statutory Guidance in relation to the safeguarding of children and vulnerable adults.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently considering all the recommendations in the Law Commission’s report on taxi and private hire regulation in England and Wales and will formally respond to the Law Commission and announce its intentions once this scrutiny is completed.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-08T14:18:27.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573844/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573844/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Taxis: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to review the regulations and guidance governing taxi and private hire vehicles working outside their primary licensing authority area.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","44444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573845","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government has an ambitious strategy for tackling congestion in our cities and towns and improving performance on our roads. This strategy includes providing significant investment in both our strategic and local road networks, as well as encouraging more sustainable transport including buses, light rail and walking and cycling. We are providing £15.2 billion between 2015 and 2021 to invest in our strategic road network. This is the biggest upgrade to our motorways and ‘A’ roads for a generation, and it is adding capacity and tackling congestion.</p><p> </p><p>On local roads we have the £12 billion Local Growth Fund to 2021 which has enabled local authorities through the Local Enterprise Partnerships to identify and secure funding for projects to enable among other things, local road improvements and sustainable local transport projects. This is on top of over £6 billion through to 2021 to councils in England to help maintain their local roads and repair potholes.</p><p> </p><p>This investment is set against the backdrop of a regulatory framework that is intended to provide better conditions for all road users through coordination and proactive management of the road network. The Traffic Management Act 2004 specifically places a network management duty on each local traffic authority in England to manage its road network to secure the expeditious movement of traffic on its own network and to facilitate the same on the network of other authorities. This can be achieved through traditional traffic management methods but increasingly also through the deployment of technology. To support this the Department is currently inviting local authorities to bid for a share of £2m to fund demonstrator projects to test these new technologies.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-12T09:40:58.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573845/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573845/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Road Traffic: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to reduce congestion in cities.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573846","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The government recognises the need to develop servicing skills to support the UK’s transition to ultra low emission vehicles (ULEVs).</p><p> </p><p>The Institute for the Motor Industry estimates there are currently around 1,000 vehicle technicians qualified to work on electric vehicles, with another 1,000 in training and due to be qualified by 2018. The 2020 Vision for English Apprenticeships supports an industry-led approach to skills training that puts employers in the driving seat of new apprenticeship standards.</p><p> </p><p>The establishment of the employer-led Institute for Apprenticeships and the introduction of an employer levy fund provides an opportunity for the ULEV sector to lead the development of training programmes to meet the skills needs they have identified.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","44567","2016-09-12T13:00:14.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573846/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573846/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Electric Vehicles: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the proportion of maintenance and repair technicians who are qualified in electric and hybrid car maintenance.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573847","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>In March 2015 the Government announced a £6.6m investment to help develop a hydrogen refuelling infrastructure. Seven successful projects are now underway to install an initial network of 12 hydrogen refuelling stations. These will support the early take-up of hydrogen fuel cell vehicles in the UK.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T12:53:40.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573847/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573847/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Alternative Fuels: Hydrogen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to support the installation of hydrogen refuelling stations.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573848","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Department has not carried out a recent detailed assessment of trends in the level of the fuel efficiency of buses. However, information on average journey times for buses is collected as part of the National Travel Survey and can be found in table NTS0311 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/456304/nts0311.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/456304/nts0311.xls</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-09T09:30:37.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573848/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573848/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Bus Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of (a) fuel efficiency and (b) journey times of buses.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573849","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Government remains fully committed to delivering the important infrastructure projects it has set out, including delivering runway capacity on the timetable set out by Sir Howard Davies.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes it is essential that expansion via any of the shortlisted schemes is accompanied by a strong package of measures to mitigate the impacts on communities and the environment, and will set out any requirements in this area on a preferred scheme promoter in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-07T16:01:25.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573849/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573849/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","London Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Government plans to impose conditions on the airport which is awarded an additional runway when making a decision on the expansion of airport capacity.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","44199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573850","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Airports Commission assessed the surface access requirements of each shortlisted scheme as part of its work in completing its Final Report and Transport for London’s (TfL) views were considered by the Commission as part of this work.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has noted Transport for London’s recent estimates of the surface access costs necessary for the expansion of Heathrow airport and understand that TfL’s figures include the costs of infrastructure schemes which may be needed to cater for wider population and economic growth up to 2040, as well as schemes which would be required to cater for additional airport users.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will consider the large amount of very detailed analysis contained in the Airports Commission’s final report, including its examination of the costs of the surface access proposals associated with airport expansion, before taking any decisions on next steps.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-07T16:07:09.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573850/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573850/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Heathrow Airport: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the documents provided by Transport for London to Greenpeace in response to a Freedom of Information request in April 2016, what steps his Department is taking to assess the accuracy of the estimate made by Transport for London that £18.4 billion would need to be spent on surface access to Heathrow Airport should that airport be awarded a third runway.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","44200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573851","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Department launched a new round of the New Stations Fund on 26 August, with up to £20 million available towards the total project cost. Promoters of new stations, including local authorities, should submit bids by 25 November.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T16:24:58.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573851/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573851/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Railways: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for local councils to bid for funds to improve local railway stations and rail services.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","44207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573852","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Airports Commission shortlisted three airport expansion schemes, two at Heathrow and one at Gatwick. We are carefully considering the evidence in relation to all three schemes. The Government accepted the Commission’s shortlist in December 2015, and has since been undertaking a programme of further work, including on air quality, to support a decision on a preferred scheme. The Government’s decision on a preferred scheme will take into account the Government’s overall plan to improve air quality and its commitments to comply with legal obligations.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-07T16:03:53.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573852/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573852/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Heathrow Airport: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Government will make it its policy that should a third runway be agreed at Heathrow Airport, that runway will not be permitted to operate if the airport breaches air quality limits.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","44201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573853","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) deals with more than 600,000 medical driver licensing applications annually. The length of time taken to deal with an individual application depends on the medical condition and whether further information is required from medical professionals.</p><p> </p><p>Between April 2016 and the end of August 2016, the average time taken for a licensing decision to be made was 38 working days. The average time for the period April 2015 to March 2016 was 53 working days.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-07T14:05:30.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573853/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573853/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how long the average anticipated response time is for a review of a driving licence due to medical reasons.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","44202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573854","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Department has appointed a joint team of solicitors/parliamentary agents from Winckworth Sherwood and Eversheds LLP to provide support in relation to the HS2 Phase 1 hybrid Bill. The current spend on this contract is £9,594,124.36.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has also appointed a joint team of solicitors/parliamentary agents from Winckworth Sherwood and Eversheds LLP to support the preparation of the HS2 Phase 2a hybrid Bill, which is expected to be deposited in 2017. The current spend on this contract is £146,265.10.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continues to instruct a team of barristers to support the HS2 project. Each barrister is remunerated at agreed government hourly rates. The spend on these barristers for the period from 2013 to the present is £2,219,872.30.</p><p> </p><p>All figures are correct up to 5 September 2016 and are exclusive of VAT.</p><p> </p><p>Since approximately 2010, the Department has also instructed a number of barristers on other HS2 related work, primarily litigation. These barristers will have been remunerated at agreed government hourly rates, but unfortunately it would involve disproportionate cost for the Department to provide precise figures.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-07T14:08:46.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573854/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573854/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","High Speed Two: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been disbursed from the public purse in legal fees for solicitors, parliamentary agents, barristers and their staff who have been working on behalf of HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","44231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573855","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The government allocated more than £600 million to support the uptake, development and manufacture of ultra low emission vehicles in the 2015 Spending Review. Our comprehensive package of support includes funding provision for research and development projects, and the scope of a new competition launched on 5 September 2016 includes battery and fuel cells.</p><p> </p><p>Further details are available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/funding-competition-low-emission-vehicle-systems-idp13" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/funding-competition-low-emission-vehicle-systems-idp13</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The UK already provides one the most comprehensive support packages for ultra low emission vehicles anywhere in the world. We shall keep the funding requirements for the OLEV program under constant review.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","44852","2016-09-12T12:42:15.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573855/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573855/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Batteries and Fuel Cells: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make additional funding available for battery and fuel cell research and development.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","44269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573856","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-08","<p>Local authorities do not have powers to independently extend eligibility. The criteria are set by statutory instrument. The Disabled Persons (Badges for Motor Vehicles) (England) Regulations 2000 (as amended) contain a number of criteria covering those who do not qualify automatically, including a provision for <strong><em>any</em></strong> permanent and substantial disability that causes inability to walk or very considerable difficulty in walking. It is the responsibility of local authorities to assess whether applicants meet any of the criteria.</p><p> </p><p>People with autism are not excluded from being issued a badge. Any permanent and substantial disability that causes very considerable difficulty walking falls within the criteria. It is the responsibility of local authorities to assess the degree of difficulty and to issue badges accordingly. We have no plans to provide badges to carers.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","44293","2016-09-08T09:29:08.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573856/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573856/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Blue Badge Scheme: Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department plans to take steps to extend eligibility for the Blue Badge scheme to the parents of children with autism.","false","Biography information for Mary Robinson","Cheadle","Mary Robinson","44292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573857","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>Clause 145 of the Policing and Crime Bill currently being considered by Parliament would enable the Secretary of State to issue Statutory Guidance to taxi and private hire licensing authorities so as to protect children, and vulnerable individuals who are 18 or over, from harm.</p><p> </p><p>There is at present no plan to bring forward further primary legislation to reform the legislative framework for taxis and private hire vehicles in the current session.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-09T09:36:02.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573857/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573857/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Taxis: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward primary legislation to regulate the taxi and private hire vehicle industries in the current session.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573858","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Department for Transport is developing the measures announced in the Queen’s speech, and the Bill will be introduced into Parliament in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-07T14:35:08.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573858/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573858/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Transport: Legislation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish the Modern Transport Bill announced in the Queen's Speech of 2016.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573859","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Analysis carried out for the government in 2015 suggested that insurance premiums are broadly equivalent between electric vehicles and their petrol or diesel equivalents.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T13:23:20.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573859/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573859/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the relative difference in insurance premiums for (a) electric vehicles and (b) diesel or petrol models.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573860","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The government recognises the need to develop servicing skills to support the UK’s transition to ultra low emission vehicles (ULEVs).</p><p> </p><p>The Institute for the Motor Industry estimates there are currently around 1,000 vehicle technicians qualified to work on electric vehicles, with another 1,000 in training and due to be qualified by 2018. The 2020 Vision for English Apprenticeships supports an industry-led approach to skills training that puts employers in the driving seat of new apprenticeship standards.</p><p> </p><p>The establishment of the employer-led Institute for Apprenticeships and the introduction of an employer levy fund provides an opportunity for the ULEV sector to lead the development of training programmes to meet the skills needs they have identified.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","44456","2016-09-12T13:00:14.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573860/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573860/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Electric Vehicles: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure vehicle technicians hold the necessary skills to work with electric vehicle technology.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573861","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government remains committed to almost every car and van in the UK being a zero emission vehicle by 2050. The Government is committed to making a success of the negotiations to leave the EU and will work hard to get the best deal for Britain. In the meantime, Departments will continue working to deliver the Government agenda.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T13:26:08.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573861/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573861/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the (a) automotive sector and (b) low emission vehicles market.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573862","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Policing and Crime Bill contains a power to enable the Secretary of State for Transport to issue Statutory Guidance to licensing authorities in relation to the safeguarding of children and vulnerable adults. There will be a consultation on draft guidance, which I intend will include guidance on Disclosure and Barring Service checks. It is expected that a consultation on this, and any Statutory Guidance, would be launched early next year.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-09T10:27:18.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573862/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573862/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Taxis: Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make Disclosure and Barring Service checks a statutory requirement for taxi and private hire vehicle driver licenses.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573863","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Delay Repay is a generous compensation scheme for longer delays, but this Government wants to go further. We are committed to improving compensation arrangements for passengers affected by shorter delays which are not covered by the current Delay Repay scheme. The previous Chancellor announced in his Autumn 2015 Spending Review that passengers will soon have access to compensation when trains are over 15 minutes late. We expect to make an announcement on this shortly.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-12T13:47:54.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573863/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573863/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Railways: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to (a) announce and (b) introduce the new arrangements for rail passenger refunds following delays; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","44576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573864","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-08","<p>The detailed timetable for this work is being developed with Network Rail. However, we would hope that it would be complete in early 2017. This work will be undertaken in close dialogue with the Greater London Authority, London Borough of Camden and Transport for London.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-08T10:07:36.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573864/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573864/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Euston Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 July 2016 to Question 41593, when the additional works on passenger train impacts from any transportation of excavated and construction materials at Euston is planned to be completed.","false","Biography information for Keir Starmer","Holborn and St Pancras","Keir Starmer","44619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573865","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>As the market for plug-in vehicles grows we have reduced the level of grant available under the Electric Vehicle Homecharge Scheme reflecting falling costs, so that Government support can be maintained and more motorists can benefit.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T13:36:02.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573865/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573865/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the reasons are for changes to the level of funding available through the electric vehicle homecharge scheme for householders wishing to install ultra-low emission vehicle charging technology at home.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573866","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Only those with off-street parking or a garage are eligible for the Electric Vehicle Homecharge Scheme which funds a dedicated home chargepoint. Some plug-in vehicle owners may only have on-street parking and be charging their vehicles at work or using the public charging network. A small number may be charging their vehicles at home using an existing domestic socket.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T13:19:46.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573866/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573866/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Electric Vehicles: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons for the difference between the number of grants taken up to be used to buy plug-in vehicles and the number of grants taken up to be used to install home charge points.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573867","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Many consumers brought forward their orders of new plug-in vehicles to before March to take advantage of the higher grant rates. The effect of this sales spike is still being felt with some vehicles ordered in February still to be delivered. This impact of the grant change will become clearer after the new registration plate in September. Registrations of ULEVs have continued to grow since the grant change.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-12T13:33:30.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573867/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573867/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Electric Vehicles: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the effect that the changes to plug-in grants from March 2016 have had on the take-up of electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573868","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department publishes statistics on average traffic speeds on locally managed ‘A’ roads in England and the Strategic Road Network. For locally managed ‘A’ roads, average speeds have decreased since 2014, when the Department started measuring speeds over the full 24 hours of the day. This is in line with the previously published statistical series which presented average speeds, on locally managed ‘A’ roads during the weekday morning peak, decreasing from 2012 to the end of that series in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The statistics for average speeds on the Strategic Road Network start in 2015-16. The latest statistics in this series (the 12 months to June 2016) presented a small decrease in average speeds compared to 2015-16 (the 12 months to March 2016).</p><p> </p><p>The Department has not undertaken a formal assessment of the reasons for the decline in average speeds. However, we believe that the decreases observed in average speeds on locally managed ‘A roads in England since 2012 are, at least in part, a result of the impact of increases in traffic on these roads. We know that people rely on roads in increasing numbers as our economy grows, and that is why, for example, we are investing £15billion in the strategic road network which will help to help tackle congestion.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, in 2012-13 there were unusually high levels of rainfall in England, which we also believe contributed to the decrease in average speeds at that time.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-12T10:17:32.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573868/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573868/answer",,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-02","Road Traffic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons for the decline in average traffic speed over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","44459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573869","Wales Office","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister.</p><p>In doing this it is working very closely with other government departments, including the Wales Office, and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-09-09T11:16:32.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573869/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573869/answer",,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-09-02","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps his Department plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573870","Wales Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Wales Office had no secondees from PwC, Deloitte, Ernst &amp; Young and KPMG or other consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-09-08T10:32:36.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573870/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573870/answer",,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-09-02","Wales Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if he will publish a list of all secondees to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573871","Wales Office","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Wales Office has not used the services of PwC, Deloitte, Ernst and Young, KPMG or other consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-09-08T10:31:38.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573871/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573871/answer",,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-09-02","Wales Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many times his Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573872","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government Equalities Office (GEO) has not employed any secondees from consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p><p> </p><p>From Financial Year 2014/15 to date, the GEO has worked with consulting firms on two occasions to support Ministers’ objectives to eliminate the Gender Pay Gap, and on these occasions at no cost to the public purse.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2014, Ernst and Young hosted the launch of the annual “Think, Act, Report” publication on the Gender Pay Gap, at no cost to the GEO. More information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/nicky-morgan-speaks-at-think-act-report-progress-report-launch" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/nicky-morgan-speaks-at-think-act-report-progress-report-launch</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2016 Deloitte produced a case study on “Think, Act, Report”, at no cost to the GEO. More information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/case-studies/deloitte-case-study" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/case-studies/deloitte-case-study</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","44351","2016-09-12T14:34:59.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573872/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573872/answer",,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-02","Government Equalities Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, if she will publish a list of all secondees to her Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573873","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-12","<p>An evaluation of the pilot fund is currently being undertaken and will be published when an announcement about the future of the fund is made in due course.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-09-12T14:37:18.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573873/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573873/answer",,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-02","Access to Elected Office for Disabled People Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, with reference to the Answers of 10 June 2015 and 22 December 2015 to Questions 700 and 19860, when she plans to (a) publish the evaluation report on the pilot Access to Elected Office Fund and (b) make a decision on whether that Fund should continue.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","44313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573874","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government Equalities Office (GEO) has not employed any secondees from consulting firms in the last three financial years.</p><p> </p><p>From Financial Year 2014/15 to date, the GEO has worked with consulting firms on two occasions to support Ministers’ objectives to eliminate the Gender Pay Gap, and on these occasions at no cost to the public purse.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2014, Ernst and Young hosted the launch of the annual “Think, Act, Report” publication on the Gender Pay Gap, at no cost to the GEO. More information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/nicky-morgan-speaks-at-think-act-report-progress-report-launch" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/nicky-morgan-speaks-at-think-act-report-progress-report-launch</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2016 Deloitte produced a case study on “Think, Act, Report”, at no cost to the GEO. More information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/case-studies/deloitte-case-study" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/case-studies/deloitte-case-study</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","44331","2016-09-12T14:34:59.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573874/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573874/answer",,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-02","Government Equalities Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many times her Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573875","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission was formed in 2007 and is an independent body. The Commission is responsible for its own staff management, including the number of case workers it employs. I have therefore asked the Commission to write to the Hon. Member with the information requested.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-09-07T16:34:47.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573875/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573875/answer",,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-02","Equality and Human Rights Commission: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many full-time equivalent caseworkers have been employed by the Equality and Human Rights Commission in each year from 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","44522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573876","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister. In doing this it is working very closely with other Government departments, including the Government Equalities Office, and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-09-12T15:58:57.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573876/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573876/answer",,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-02","Government Equalities Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government Equalities Office has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps the Government Equalities Office plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573877","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>Where a separated couple have joint custody for their children, only one of them will receive financial assistance for those children through Universal Credit. The separated couple may jointly nominate which of them that will be. The parent who receives financial support is the one whom the child normally lives with, but if the child normally lives with both, then it is the parent who has main responsibility for the child. This is to be decided by the parents, or failing that, the Secretary of State if the parents cannot agree or if the Secretary of State does not think that the nomination accurately reflects the arrangement. HM Revenue &amp; Customs administer Child Tax Credit and Child Benefit and the rules similarly require that payment is directed towards the person who is mainly responsible for the child, so that at any one time, only one person can be entitled to receive payments in respect of a particular child.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-12T12:33:55.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573877/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573877/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Children: Separated People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether there is provision to ensure that both parents in a separated couple receive financial assistance for their children when joint custody has been approved.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","44174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573878","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister. In doing this it is working very closely with other government departments, including the Department for Work and Pensions and a wide range of other interested parties.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-12T16:21:51.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573878/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573878/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to prepare for the UK to leave the EU since 23 June 2016; and what further such steps his Department plans to take in the remainder of 2016.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","44256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573879","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>For DWP purposes a statement of fitness for work (SOFFW) can be obtained from a GP at no cost to the claimant.</p><p> </p><p>DWP does not refund postage or other costs associated with obtaining a SOFFW. Claimants are notified when making a claim that there is a requirement to supply a SOFFW to meet the ESA entitlement conditions. To support this DWP provides options for postage, either a Freepost Licence code or a pre-paid envelope at no cost to the claimant. These are handled by Royal Mail and subject to their governance and safeguarding arrangements.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-07T15:33:17.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573879/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573879/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Social Security Benefits: Medical Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether welfare claimants receive refunds for postage and other costs incurred in obtaining a doctor's certificate as required by his Department and ensuring its safe transmission by post.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","44191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573880","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-07","<p>Under the Personal Protective Equipment Regulations 2002 it is a criminal offence to place on the market personal protective equipment that does not comply with the regulations or to supply any such equipment unless it is safe. Trading Standards are responsible for taking appropriate action against personal protective equipment that does not comply with the Regulations. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy continues to work closely with Trading Standards to ensure that any Personal Protective Equipment on the market is safe.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-07T13:19:38.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573880/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573880/answer",,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-02","Safety: Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that personal protective equipment which does not comply with the Personal Protective Equipment Regulations 2002 is not used in the UK.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","44192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573881","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-07","<p>The new Personal Protective Equipment Regulation adopted earlier this year, will apply from 21 April 2018 and while it does not need transposing into UK legislation there will need to be implementing UK legislation to provide for enforcement and penalties. The Government will consult on these provisions in due course.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-07T13:16:13.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573881/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573881/answer",,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-02","Safety: Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to take steps to incorporate into UK law the new personal protective equipment regulations.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","44193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573882","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>Equality legislation for Disabled People is devolved to the Northern Ireland Assembly.</p><p>In Great Britain, the Equality Act 2010 defines disability as “a physical or mental impairment which has a substantial and long-term adverse effect on a person’s ability to carry out normal day-today activities”. Where an employee/applicant or service-user has a condition that fits the definition of a disability, they are protected under the 2010 Act. Employers and service-providers are therefore required to make reasonable adjustments available in order to ensure that disabled people are not placed at a substantial disadvantage compared to those who do not have a disability.</p><p> </p><p>It is for the courts to decide, on a case-by-case basis, whether there has been disability discrimination where a reasonable adjustment has not been made available.</p><p> </p><p>For those who need additional support over and above that which is a reasonable adjustment, Access to Work can help. Access to Work provides practical and financial support with the additional costs faced by individuals whose health or disability affects the way they do their job. Access to Work continues to support over 36,000 people per year take up or retain employment.</p><p> </p><p>Disability Confident, on which this Department leads, was launched by the then Prime Minister in July 2013 to challenge perceptions, engage employers and promote good practice.</p><p> </p><p>Disability Confident is about creating a movement for change - getting employers to think differently about disability and to take action to improve how they attract, recruit and retain disabled workers.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T15:56:41.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573882/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573882/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will review the adequacy of the level of protection against discrimination in employment, training and career development for people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","44169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573883","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to improving the life chances of disabled people and has made a commitment to halve the employment gap between disabled and non-disabled people.</p><p>The Government is working with employers through Disability Confident to challenge attitudes towards disability and ensure that disabled people have the opportunities to fulfil their potential and realise their aspirations. Since 2013 the number of disabled people in work has increased by almost half a million (493,000). Nearly 3.4 million disabled people are now in employment.</p><p>Access to Work provides practical and financial support with the additional costs faced by individuals whose heath or disability affects the way they do their job. 36,470 individuals were helped by Access to Work in the 2015/16 including record numbers of people with learning disabilities, mental health conditions and young people. Last year’s Spending review announced a real-terms increase in funding for access to work starting in 16/17 to enable the scheme to help a further 25,000 people by the end of the parliament.</p><p>Work Choice is a voluntary contracted specialist disability employment programme introduced in 2010 and helps people with disabilities whose needs cannot be met through other employment programmes, Access to Work or workplace adjustments. It provides individually tailored support (e.g. job search skills, basic training, and work placements) for disabled people who face the most complex employment barriers to find and stay in work.</p><p>Later this year, we will produce a Green Paper exploring a range of options to close the disability employment gap and transform the lives and prospects of disabled people, and conduct a consultation which will reach out to disabled people and their representative organisations.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T16:56:44.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573883/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573883/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to improve the life chances of people with disabilities.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","44170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573884","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>Last year, we undertook a call for evidence on issues around section 75 debt and employers in multi-employer schemes and have been actively considering the responses.</p><p> </p><p>More recently, we have been engaging direct with interested parties as we seek to ensure the appropriate balance between protection for members and burdens on employers.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-07T12:56:12.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573884/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573884/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on section 75 employer debt in pension funds; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","44209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573885","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>Where parents of disabled children would like to go out to work, DWP wants to make it easier for them to do so. Jobcentre Plus Work Coaches provide personalised support, tailored to meet the needs and requirements of the claimant, helping them to find work that fits with their individual circumstances. Work Coaches will also endeavour to support the claimant to overcome barriers that might make finding a job more difficult and will work with the individual to identify the most appropriate help available.</p><p> </p><p>Under Universal Credit, extra financial support is available to parents for each dependent child who is disabled. Universal Credit also provides working parents with help with childcare costs. In April 2016, we extended this support to cover up to 85% of the eligible costs of childcare.</p><p> </p><p>Parents of disabled children also receive help with childcare through the free childcare entitlements. All three and four year olds are entitled to 15 hours of free childcare per week, and we are extending this free entitlement to 30 hours per week for working parents of three and four year olds. In addition, two year olds are entitled to 15 hours of free childcare if they have a current statement of special educational need or an education, health and care plan, or receive Disability Living Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education is consulting on additional funding for children with special education needs and disabilities as part of its consultation on early years funding which closes on 22 September 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Working parents of disabled children will also benefit from extra support under Tax-Free Childcare which will be introduced from early 2017. This will provide Government support with childcare costs of up to £4,000 per year for a disabled child up to the age of 17.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-07T16:13:55.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573885/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573885/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Disability: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to support the parents of children with special educational needs and disabilities to enable them to find employment.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","44208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573886","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>We do not have any information about numbers of employers who may be liable for a section 75 debt. This is a matter between the employer and the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not provide advice to any employers about potential section 75 debts. The Pensions Regulator provides a range of information and guidance on all matters related to pensions scheme funding. However, employers or former employers should take their own professional and legal advice about their liabilities.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-07T13:03:14.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573886/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573886/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many partnerships have been adversely affected by section 75 employer debt in pension funds; how many such partnerships have been (a) converted to limited liability and (b) declared insolvent; and what advice his Department has provided to partnerships facing potential section 75 employer debts.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","44211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573887","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government is aware of the fact that some parts of the Defined Benefit (DB) pension sector are concerned about the current economic climate, but the situation is very mixed, and the experiences of schemes differ. We do not believe there is a systemic problem but we continually look at ways to improve the affordability of schemes.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-12T13:16:01.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573887/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573887/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to improve the affordability of existing pension schemes for companies.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","44305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573888","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-12T11:49:07.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573888/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573888/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate the number of working parents and carers receiving universal credit who will be required to work increased hours under in-work conditionality that (a) are unable to work full-time hours and (b) will require flexible working arrangements.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","44315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573889","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) operational data is derived from reports made under duties contained in the Reporting of Injuries and Dangerous Occurrences Regulations 2013 (RIDDOR) (and earlier versions). It is as follows:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No. of reported injuries in underground mines in Great Britain* **</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2011 – 31 March 2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>204</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2012 – 31 March 2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>146</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2013 – 31 March 2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>114</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2014 – 31 March 2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>75</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2015 – 31 March 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>52</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>1 April 2016 – 31 August 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>21</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>*</strong> A key change to RIDDOR occurred in April 2012, ie the threshold for reporting of those injuries to workers which result in the person being incapacitated for more than three days changed to over seven days.</p><p> </p><p>** It should be noted that the reducing trend is, in part, due to the reduction in the number of large working mines in recent years.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T12:31:17.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573889/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573889/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Mining: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many accidents have occurred in mines in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573890","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-08","<p>No existing legacy benefit claimant has yet been moved onto Universal Credit. The managed migration of existing legacy benefit claimants will commence in July 2019 and be completed in March 2022.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-08T12:14:54.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573890/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573890/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573890/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have transferred to universal credit since its implementation; and how many of those people have challenged the payment accredited to them.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","44284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573891","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-08","<p>The next stages of the delivery of Universal Credit were set out by the Work and Pensions Secretary in a Written Statement to Parliament on 20 July. The rollout schedule from May 2016 through to March 2017 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/539516/universal-credit-transition-rollout-schedule-phase-1-to-3-2016-to-2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/539516/universal-credit-transition-rollout-schedule-phase-1-to-3-2016-to-2017.pdf</a></p><p>Further details of the sites rolling out from April 2017 will be announced later this year.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-08T16:57:05.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573891/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573891/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the timetable is for its plans to roll-out universal credit on a constituency-by-constituency basis; and whether that timetable includes internal deadlines for separate phases of that roll-out.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","44285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573892","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) has received one representation on recent incidents, from the hon. Member for Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland. HSE has carried out a variety of interventions with the operators of Boulby mine, ranging from the serving of Prohibition Notices to a detailed assessment of their safety and competency management systems. HSE is reviewing the circumstances of a number of recent incidents with a view to taking further enforcement action if appropriate.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T12:22:52.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573892/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573892/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Mining: Redcar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has received on the recent fatalities at the Boulby Potash mine; and whether his Department has made an assessment of the need to take any such action in respect of those fatalities.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573893","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Health and Safety Executive does not hold such information.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-07T16:24:58.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573893/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573893/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Mining: Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of health and safety incidents which have taken place in the mining industry when employees were working on shift patterns of more than (a) eight, (b) 10 and (c) 12 hours.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573894","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department always considers a range of evidence from a variety of sources when making a decision on an individual’s PIP claim and is robust in asking for further information if it feels this will be beneficial for the claimant. In addition, the department will always consider any additional evidence provided at the Mandatory Reconsideration or appeal stage.<strong> </strong></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T13:49:46.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573894/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573894/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will bring forward proposals to ensure mandatory assessment of sources of additional evidence supplied by claimants of personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","44283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573895","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T11:09:02.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573895/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573895/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Personal Independence Payment: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claims for personal independence payments included requests to consider additional evidence in (a) Glasgow Central constituency, (b) Glasgow and (c) Scotland since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","44281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573896","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>We are about to begin negotiations for Britain’s future relationship with Europe and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","44853","2016-09-07T13:10:17.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573896/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573896/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential implications for his Department's policy on the uprating of the pensions of British people living abroad of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","44268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573897","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-07","<p>During its interventions, HSE assesses how dutyholders provide for and manage the provision of safety-critical competence at mines. This includes assessing whether staff with responsibility for safety-critical tasks are sufficiently experienced and resourced.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-07T16:22:53.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573897/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573897/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Mining: Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the relationship between staffing levels and health and safety incidents in mines.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573898","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The assessment for Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is designed to treat people as individuals, considering the impact of their impairment or health condition on their everyday life and how each claimant has personally adapted to living with a disability.</p><p> </p><p>The assessment is carried out by registered health professionals who have specialist training in assessing the impact of disability and health conditions on an individual’s functional ability, including some rare conditions. Prior to carrying out an assessment they routinely refresh their knowledge of any condition with which they are not fully familiar.</p><p> </p><p>The PIP Assessment Guide for Health Professionals includes guidance on the assessment criteria and how they should be applied. This guidance can be accessed on the gov.uk website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/449043/pip-assessment-guide.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/449043/pip-assessment-guide.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Since its inception, all aspects of the PIP assessment process have been continually reviewed and refined in order to improve its efficiency, effectiveness and the experience of all claimants including those with rare conditions. As part of this continuous improvement process, Paul Gray CB is undertaking the second independent review of the PIP assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The review will look at all stages of the PIP process, with a particular focus on the use of further evidence in the claim process, data sharing and the claimant experience. The terms of reference were published in July and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/534681/terms-of-reference-pip-second-independent-review.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/534681/terms-of-reference-pip-second-independent-review.pdf</a>. The report will be laid before Parliament by April 2017.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","44113","2016-09-12T14:17:00.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573898/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573898/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to improve how people with rare medical conditions are assessed for personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","44265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573899","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>We are committed to ensuring that the Personal Independence Payment (PIP) assessment process works effectively across the spectrum of disabilities and health conditions, including rare conditions.</p><p> </p><p>I, along with my officials, meet regularly with disability representative groups, including members of our Implementation Stakeholder Forum which hears views from a wide range of organisations representing and supporting disabled people, including those with rare conditions. We have worked extensively with them to make improvements to guidance, training and audit procedures in order to ensure a quality service for all claimants including those with rare conditions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","44112","2016-09-12T13:58:50.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573899/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573899/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on improving how people with rare medical conditions are assessed for personal independence payments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","44266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573900","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Mines Regulations 2014 replaced all previous legislation relating to health and safety in mines. They provide a comprehensive and simple goal-setting legal framework to ensure that mine operators provide all the necessary protection for mineworkers and others from the inherent hazards in mining.</p><p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) targets interventions with the underground mining dutyholders and a mine’s past safety and health performance is taken into account when deciding on the detail of specific interventions.</p><p> </p><p>HSE investigates reported accidents in mines in line with the criteria set out in its Incident Selection Criteria. Investigations focus on determining both the immediate and underlying causes in order to prevent recurrence. HSE also make recommendations for improved methods of work and systems for the wider industry if necessary and holds dutyholders to account through proportional enforcement where appropriate.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-08T11:01:58.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573900/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573900/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Mining: Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to help prevent accidents in the mining industry.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573901","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Government does not provide individual businesses or the mining industry with financial support to help them meet their health and safety duties. Protection of employees, or others who may be affected by work activities, is the responsibility of those who create the health and safety risks. The Health and Safety Executive’s programme of work for the mines industry is described further on its website (<a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/mining/programme.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/mining/programme.htm</a>).</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-08T11:11:23.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573901/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573901/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Mining: Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make financial support available to improve health and safety (a) at Boulby Potash mine and (b) in the mining industry.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","44375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573902","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-12T12:39:52.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573902/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573902/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish a list of all secondees to his Department from (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what the role was of each of those secondees.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573903","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>We have made a significant commitment to supporting people through the welfare system to seek to increase their earnings in work. We are testing a range of approaches.</p><p>This includes ongoing trials on how in-work progression can be supported by work coaches. This will help us further develop the work coach role to support in-work claimants, including working parents and Carers.</p><p>We have also put in place a substantial programme of learning and ongoing support for work coaches. All coaches receive face-to-face classroom learning which focuses on both the technical delivery steps and importantly the transformational change of delivering in-work progression, as well as consolidation post-completion.</p><p>Many of the skills that work coaches develop and utilise when working with out-of-work claimants are equally applicable to in-work claimants, and they will bring these skills to bear in addition to the extra learning.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-12T12:29:56.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573903/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573903/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department plans to take to train Jobcentre Plus advisors to support working parents and carers in in-work progression under universal credit.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","44316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573904","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>A decision on whether to add Dupuytren’s contracture to the list of prescribed diseases can only be made after the potential impacts and other considerations have been fully evaluated. We will announce our response to the Industrial Injuries Advisory Council’s recommendation in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-12T15:06:11.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573904/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573904/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit: Dupuytren's Contracture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 35941 and with reference to the Answer of 12 January 2016 to Question 21220, on industrial injuries disablement benefit: Durpuytren's contracture, for what reasons a decision has not yet been made on whether to add that condition to the list of industrial injuries disablement benefit diseases.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","44311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573905","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-15","<p>We are unable to provide the requested information on the number of times the Department for Work and Pensions has used the services of consulting firms, including details of the work undertaken and cost to the public purse for each occasion. To do so would incur a disproportional cost to the Department because of how the data is held on our systems, and the time and resource required for extracting and analysing it.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-15T14:56:30.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573905/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573905/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times his Department has used the services of (a) PwC, (b) Deloitte, (c) Ernst and Young, (d) KPMG and (e) other consulting firms in the last three financial years; and what (i) work was undertaken and (ii) the cost to the public purse was on each such occasion.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","44361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573906","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-08","<p>If a physical assessment of the musculoskeletal system is required, it is largely non-touch and based on observing ‘active movements’ – i.e. movements carried out under the direction of, but without the physical intervention of, the Healthcare Professional.</p><p> </p><p>The impact on a claimant undergoing this type of assessment should therefore be negligible.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-08T15:51:18.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573906/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573906/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the impact of protocols on touching disability benefit assessment centre attendees on the accessibility of these sites to those who struggle to stand unaided.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","44378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573907","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The information requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-12T11:42:29.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573907/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/573907/answer",,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate how many parents and carers in receipt of universal credit will require childcare after transition to in-work conditionality.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","44314"
